Here are both approaches:

## 1. Register the route (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. ProductListPage â€” navigate on tap

```xml
<!-- ProductListPage.xaml -->
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Products}"
                SelectionMode="Single"
                SelectionChangedCommand="{Binding ProductSelectedCommand}"
                SelectionChangedCommandParameter="{Binding SelectedItem,
                    Source={RelativeSource Self}}">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate x:DataType="models:Product">
            <VerticalStackLayout Padding="10">
                <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="18" />
                <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='${0:F2}'}" />
            </VerticalStackLayout>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>
```

```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductListViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    ObservableCollection<Product> products;

    // â”€â”€ Approach A: pass just the ID as a query-string parameter â”€â”€
    [RelayCommand]
    async Task ProductSelectedById(Product product)
    {
        if (product is null) return;
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");
    }

    // â”€â”€ Approach B: pass the full Product object â”€â”€
    [RelayCommand]
    async Task ProductSelected(Product product)
    {
        if (product is null) return;

        var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        {
            { "product", product }
        };
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
    }
}
```

## 3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable`

```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    string productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A â€” string ID from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, DB, etc.
        }

        // Approach B â€” full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

## Key differences

| | **Query string (`?id=...`)** | **ShellNavigationQueryParameters** |
|---|---|---|
| Data type | String only | Any object |
| Serialization | Values are URI-encoded | No serialization â€” passed by reference |
| Use case | Simple IDs, small values | Complex objects, avoid extra lookups |
| Deep-link friendly | âś… Yes | âťŚ No (in-process only) |

**Tips:**
- Always `await` `GoToAsync` â€” fire-and-forget causes race conditions.
- Wire `ProductDetailsPage.BindingContext` to `ProductDetailsViewModel` via DI so `ApplyQueryAttributes` is called automatically.
- Both approaches can coexist in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` â€” Shell calls it once with all provided keys.
